		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr><td><P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>
   Many readers of this site have gotten on my case about chiding
people for their poorly written e-mails to me.  As some of you are
aware, I often reprimand my readers for bad spelling, incorrect
grammar and syntax, and other manifestations of poor English usage
skills.<P>

   Recently, a friend of mine (who will remain nameless, so his
current employer won't know that he doesn't like his job), who has
expressed an interest in game design, sent me the URL of an
article that includes the following page:<P>

<a href="http://www.gamasutra.com/features/game_design/19980320/hiring_designers_02.htm">www.gamasutra.com/features/game_design/19980320/hiring_designers_02.htm</a><P>

   Let this be a lesson to all of you.  What's written at that
link is very true for <I>lots</I> of professions, not just that of
game designer.  It's a fact: if someone can't write well, he/she
is probably going to come across as unintelligent (like some of
the people who write to me), and I'm not going to say that such a
perception isn't warranted.  As the Gamasutra article suggests,
the ability to write well indicates lucidity of thought and
cohesiveness of reason better than just about anything else, while
poorly written text betrays puerile, fragmented, and/or
uncommitted thought processes, particularly without the benefit of
other credentials that prove the writer's intelligence.<P>

   Someone who wants to be heard will want to be understood, and
that requires structured thought and communication.  There's no
way around it.  A few mistakes are forgivable, but come to me with
excessive slang or insufficient punctuation or egregiously spelled
words or inefficiently communicated ideas, and I'll treat you like
the fourth-rate intellectual slob that you are.  Then, I'll go eat
my lunch and do it some more.<P>

   Period.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Greetings Milo,<P>
 
 This is a question about the software you use to make all the models and render the models.  Do you use software created by an independent 3rd party, use software that is in the market (Softimage, Maya and 3D Studio Max for example) or do you guys at verant write your own modelling software.<P>
 
 The second part is about rendering.  How complex are the rendering algorithms in the game as it has to be run in real time with data being sent over the internet.  The same goes for rendering as does for the modelling, do you make the software, someone else or is it commercially available.<P>
 
 With the models.  Are they designed to be run only within the games rendering or are lesser polygon count versions of other models which can be rendered in much higher quality but not at real time.<P>
 
 A final question relates to your portfolio and show-reels.  How much work did you have to show off and what quality was it before you broke into the game industry?  I ask because I'm about to do my final year of a course called BSc Visualisation.  On it we learn everything from modelling to writing the software to render and model and all aspects of game physics and AI.  As it is my last year I'm looking for all the advice I can get before making my way out into the game / film industry... hopefully.<P>
 
 Martin Wright


<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Good questions, Mr. Wright.<P>

   Most of us artists use commercially available software -- Maya,
3D Studio MAX, Adobe Photoshop, etc.  Our world builders use
in-house software to build dungeons.<P>

   As far as I know, our graphics engines are also cooked in-house.
Our programmers write plug-ins that allow us artists to export
our work to formats suitable for their custom code.<P>

   The models are WYSIWYG.<P>

   I got into the gaming industry a long time ago (1991), and all
I had to show my potential employer at the time was some of
the two-dimensional, 4-bit color work that I did on the Amiga
CRPG game that I, Brad McQuaid, and Steve Clover were
completing in our spare time.  Nowadays, one has to have a
much more impressive portfolio, and I've come to know so many
people in this industry over the years that I've never actually had
to put together anything like the five minute MTV commercials
that some artists use to sell themselves.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

